body:
Stop writing `JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj))` — it loses Dates, Maps, Sets, undefined, functions, and chokes on circular refs.

Modern browsers and Node 17+ have `structuredClone()`:

```js
const clone = structuredClone(original);
// Handles Dates, Maps, Sets, circular refs, typed arrays, etc.
```

Replace verbose `&&` chains with `?.`:

```js
// ❌ Verbose
const city = user && user.address && user.address.city;

// ✅ Clean
const city = user?.address?.city;

// Also works for function calls
const result = obj.method?.();  // undefined if method doesn't exist
```

`Array.from()` accepts a map function as its second argument — cleaner than `.map()` after `.fill()`.

```js
// ❌ Verbose
const zeros = new Array(5).fill(0);
const squares = zeros.map((_, i) => i * i);

// ✅ Clean
const squares = Array.from({ length: 5 }, (_, i) => i * i);
// [0, 1, 4, 9, 16]
```

You can provide defaults AND rename in one go:

```js
const { name: userName = 'Anonymous', age = 18 } = user;
// userName = user.name (or 'Anonymous')
// age = user.age (or 18)
```

Also works with function params:
```js
function greet({ name = 'Anonymous' } = {}) { ... }
```

`Set.has()` is O(1), `Array.includes()` is O(n).

```js
// ❌ Slow for large arrays
const allowed = ['admin', 'editor', 'moderator'];
if (allowed.includes(role)) { ... }

// ✅ Fast — O(1) lookup
const allowed = new Set(['admin', 'editor', 'moderator']);
if (allowed.has(role)) { ... }
```

Rule of thumb: if you call `.includes()` more than once on the same array, convert to Set.

Unlike `Promise.all()` which rejects on the first failure, `Promise.allSettled()` waits for all and reports status:

```js
const results = await Promise.allSettled([
  fetch('/api/a'),
  fetch('/api/b'),
  fetch('/api/c'),
]);

results.forEach(r => {
  if (r.status === 'fulfilled') console.log(r.value);
  else console.error(r.reason);
});
```

Perfect for parallel fetches where some failures are acceptable.

Need to cancel an in-flight fetch (e.g., user typed again)? Use `AbortController`:

```js
const controller = new AbortController();

fetch('/api/search?q=foo', { signal: controller.signal })
  .then(r => r.json())
  .catch(err => {
    if (err.name === 'AbortError') return; // expected
    throw err;
  });

// Later, cancel it:
controller.abort();
```

Essential for search-as-you-type UIs.

For unique IDs, use the built-in crypto module:

```js
crypto.randomUUID();
// 'a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890'
```

It's a proper UUID v4 (122 bits of entropy). `Math.random().toString(36)` is fine for non-security use but collisions are more likely with enough IDs.

Template literals can be tagged with a function that pre-processes parts:

```js
function html(strings, ...values) {
  return strings.reduce((acc, str, i) => {
    const val = values[i] ?? '';
    return acc + str + String(val).replace(/[<>&]/g, c =>
      ({ '<': '&lt;', '>': '&gt;', '&': '&amp;' }[c]));
  }, '');
}

const userInput = '<script>alert(1)</script>';
const safe = html`<div>${userInput}</div>`;
// <div>&lt;script&gt;alert(1)&lt;/script&gt;</div>
```

This is how lit-html and other libraries escape user content safely.

`forEach` doesn't support `break` or early return — use `for...of` instead:

```js
// ❌ Can't break out of forEach
arr.forEach(item => {
  if (item === target) return;  // doesn't do what you think!
  console.log(item);
});

// ✅ for...of supports break
for (const item of arr) {
  if (item === target) break;
  console.log(item);
}
```

`.some()` and `.every()` also short-circuit — useful for early-exit searches.

ES2021 added compound assignment for nullish and logical OR:

```js
// Old way
if (obj.prop == null) obj.prop = 'default';

// New way
obj.prop ??= 'default';  // assign only if null/undefined
obj.count ||= 1;         // assign only if falsy
obj.active &&= false;    // assign only if truthy
```

In `.mjs` files (or with `"type": "module"` in package.json), you can use `await` at the top level — no wrapping IIFE needed:

```js
// top-level await in app.mjs
const data = await fetch('/api/data').then(r => r.json());
console.log(data);
```

Useful for scripts and config files. Doesn't work in CommonJS (`.cjs` / plain `.js`).

Iterating an object's entries is cleaner than `for...in` + `hasOwnProperty` check:

```js
const obj = { a: 1, b: 2, c: 3 };

// ✅ Clean
for (const [key, value] of Object.entries(obj)) {
  console.log(key, value);
}

// Transform to array
const doubled = Object.fromEntries(
  Object.entries(obj).map(([k, v]) => [k, v * 2])
);
```

ES2023 added `findLast` / `findLastIndex` — find the LAST matching element without reversing:

```js
const arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 4, 3];

// Old way
[...arr].reverse().find(x => x === 4);  // mutates copy, awkward

// New way (ES2023)
arr.findLast(x => x === 4);  // 4 (the second occurrence)
arr.findLastIndex(x => x === 4);  // 5
```
